      <h1 class="header-title" style="text-align: center;">Why Turtle Shelter Project?</h1>
      <br>
      
      <div class="content">
        <div class="card">
          <img src="NCH-Winter-Emergency-Shelters.png" alt="Emergency Shelters">
        </div>
        <br>
        <p>
          Foam clothing, invented by survival expert Jim Phillips, provides life-saving insulation in freezing temperatures, even when wet. Unlike traditional materials like cotton, this technology uses synthetic, breathable fabrics paired with open-cell polyurethane foam to wick moisture and retain body heat. This innovation has the potential to protect vulnerable populations from cold-related injuries like hypothermia and frostbite, which disproportionately impact those experiencing homelessness.
        </p>
        <br>
        <p>
          Turtle Shelter Project's founder, Jen, notes: <span style="font-style: italic;">“Isn’t a person who is homeless living in their emergency right this very moment?”</span> This clothing could ease their suffering, offering warmth, hope, and a step toward restoring dignity.
        </p>
        <br>
        <p>
          The Turtle Shelter foam vest, designed to harness body heat even in the harshest conditions, is an affordable adaptation of this technology. While it has been marketed to emergency preparedness and extreme sports enthusiasts, its real potential lies in aiding communities that lack comprehensive winter response plans. By addressing gaps in shelter access, particularly in rural areas or during milder cold weather when resources are scarce, foam clothing offers a practical, life-saving solution for those left without refuge from the cold.
        </p>
